Similar to my other things posted here, this comes from the code I give to my students to help them to start developing 3-D graphics. Part of this code creates a base cube and then a series of other classes apply different distortions on the cube. In this case the vertices of the cube are twisted by an increasing amount as you move up the cube. As this goes from 0 degrees at the bottom up to 90 at the top, each side sort of replaces its neighbour.

A couple of nice touches. Firstly is the fact that the facets of the underlying triangles catches the light both in the real world model as well as in the graphics, which means I got the lighting model in my code right! Secondly, if held to the light correctly the model casts a circular shadow.

As well as being a nice solid model if printed as is, if scaled along its height and printed in vase mode it makes a very effective vase. As shown in the last picture.

Yep had some issues :) You can try running it on the 5Volts of the stopper plug on the board. But the chances are high that the sensor is not working at all or doesnt work realible at 5v. The specs say 6V min (up to 24v, as far as i remember..to lazy to look it up)
So the 12v out of the power supply are a good source. BUT you cant send the 12v back in the signal pin of you board. it WILL fry your board! What you need is a voltage divider. made an ugly sketch for you :) https://cloud.motey.org/index.php/s/op5WG92Kgu4Co7Z
Before you plugin in the board plug, wire the sensor and verify the output voltage of the signal wire not to be higher as 5v when the sensor is triggered.
This is a very simple and not the safest approach. There are some better designs on the net (with z-diode, etc)

title: Ball Bearing Spool Holder for Monoprice Select Mini (Malyan M200)

description.text:
A ball-bearing spool holder for the Monoprice Select Mini. Replaces the stock spool holder (fits on the tabs used by the stock spool holder). Requires one 5/16"x5" bolt, one 5/16" lock nut, and three 608 bearings. (Links to the items I used are provided for illustrative purposes, not as recommendations for where to purchase.)

To assemble:

  1. Print the Spool Holder Beginning (with supports). Then push the bolt through from the hexahedral side of the hole in the middle of the print. The fit should be tight, so a little bit of force may be required.
  2. Print the Spool Holder Spacer. Then slide the print onto the bolt.
  3. Print one copy of the Spool Holder Center (with supports). Then push a 608 bearing into the side with the flange (should be flush with the end of the print once seated). The fit should be tight, so a little bit of force may be required. Similarly, push a 608 bearing into the opposite side of the print (it will stick halfway out of the print). Slide the print onto the bolt (flange side towards the Spool Holder Beginning).
  4. Print a second copy of the Spool Holder Center (with supports). Then push a 608 bearing into the side with the flange (should be flush with the end of the print once seated). Slide the print onto the bolt (flange side away from the Spool Holder Beginning).
  5. Print the Spool Holder End (with supports). Then push the lock nut into the hexahedral side of the hole in the middle of the print. The fit should be tight, so a little bit of force may be required. Screw the spool holder end onto the end of the bolt (should be tight enough to lock, but not much more).

description.text:
These files allow you to turn your 3D printer into a plotter that uses regular sharpies or double-sided sharpies (for the extra-fine end). It can be used to draw anything of course, but it was designed with PCB etching in mind.

The bracket is currently meant to attach to a Printrbot Simple Metal, but all files are included as STL and SKP (sketchup). The device is modular, so modifications to mount to your printer are minimal.

There are different size springs for different size pens. Normally the longest one is for regular sharpies and the medium one for the double ended sharpies. However, through variance between prints, sometimes you may want to go a size down to make sure it's not too tight, that spring should be easy to squish.

The holder's height is adjustable, and all you need are an elastic and a 1cm M3 + nut or 1/2 inch 4-40 screw + nut

Fore a step by step guide to the basic plotting, and to make sure that the pen hops between segments, check out my instructables here https://www.instructables.com/id/Turn-Your-3D-Printer-Into-a-Plotter/

For more on the PBC etching or drawing on thicker substrates check out this second instructables https://www.instructables.com/id/3D-Printer-PCB-Etching/

description.text:
The original Coffee Cup by @barspin is easily the most used item I printed so far.

I printed two cups using the original models but had problems to get the second (black cup) watertight. I solved that with a thin layer of glue in the problematic area. But that spoiled the food-safety and you can see it "shimmering".

I wondered why it was not being watertight and checked the model. It contains of two volume objects. One is to make the bottom plain and printable without supports. It sits inside the real model of the cup and they are slightly separated.

Using Simplify 3D with a good adjusted printer and clean printing filament does result in a small gap at the bottom part of the cup which makes it harder to be fully watertight. It also does not sit plain anymore after some days of usage and with liquid getting into the small gap when washing dishes.

I used Meshmixer to remove the extra object and made the model having a "real" flat surface instead. That model printed much better and has still a flat base after weeks of daily usage.

There are three pictures. Two of them show the original model printed with white and black BDP / GreenTec which is form stable for temperatures up to 110° C and is food-proof!

The third shows the fixed model printed with "BDP Flax" in comparison to the normal white BDP. The usage times of both cups are similar at that point and both freshly cleaned. One can easily see how the BDP Flax is taking much less stains from the coffee. It also feels more "expensive" and a bit like "ceramic". Needles to say that I love this filament!

This is a small device for quickly loading rounds into 9mm handgun magazines. It seems that every time I go to the range with friends I'm the only one who has one of these, and everyone is always "borrowing" mine! This device is very useful for loading new magazines with very stiff springs, or loading using gloves in cold weather. I have tested it with Beretta, Sig-Sauer, Springfield, and Ruger magazines. Others have printed and tested it with Smith & Wesson, Steyr, and FN/Browning magazines. It loads both single and double-stack magazines, and should work with any caliber which is dimensionally similar to 9x19mm.
OPERATION: The speed loader is placed on top of the magazine, and pressed downwards (see figures). A small boss depresses the top round in the magazine and in turn compresses the magazine spring. Another round is then loaded, from the front, and pressed backward against the boss. The speed loader is then lifted slightly so the new round can be fully seated. This process is repeated until the magazine is fully loaded.
CAUTION: Firearms, ammunition, and magazines should only be handled by trained adults. This design is provided "as is" without any warranty.

The speed loader should be printed in the default orientation, even though it looks "upside-down," with the small flat surface on the build plate. Printing in this orientation requires a single bridging extrusion, so make sure that your slicer & printer are dialed in properly. If printed in this orientation no support is required.
The speed loader should be printed with 100% infill for strength.
I have had good luck at 0.2 mm/layer, with 2 perimeters, using Slic3r and a Makergear M2.

title: PWM mount kit for variable fan speed on FlashForge Creator Pro

description.text:
Being able to regulate the speed of the cooling fan, allows to fine-tune print quality. Some filaments like flexible PLA need all the cooling they can get, while filaments like ABS will warp and delaminate if they are cooled too aggressively. If you plan to use my highly optimized single-extruder cooling duct, having a way to control the fan speed is simply essential.

Unfortunately the FlashForge Creator pro lacks a fan speed controller, because the fan is hooked up to the EXTRA output of the mainboard, which can only be toggled, it has no PWM capabilities. It is possible to create and install a custom build of Sailfish that emulates PWM, but this can only be configured manually before starting a print, and it does not react to commands in the G-code or X3G file.

There is a simple way to obtain fan speed control after all: insert a PWM controller in between the EXTRA output and the fan. This requires only minimal changes to the printer and allows to instantly change the speed at any moment. You need a PWM controller that works at 24V DC, anything will do if it switches not significantly faster than 1 kHz.

I bought a cheapo PWM controller on AliExpress that accepts between 12 and 36 V, and designed a bracket to mount one inside the printer, as well as a box to mount the potentiometer. This particular board is 55x35 mm, which is easy to mount inside the enclosure. You may need to redesign the mounting bracket depending on your particular controller board, but the potentiometer housing should be usable for most models.

I used ø2.2 mm 6.5 mm self-tapping screws to mount the PCB to the bracket (which is simply glued into the printer), and ø2.9 mm 9 mm screws to mount the potentiometer.

I did have to change the timing capacitor on my particular PWM board, because it switched at 30kHz, which is way too fast for the fan. I tuned the frequency down to only 200 Hz, which works perfectly. Any frequency below 2kHz is probably OK.

Beware! If you try a hack like this, make sure not to short-circuit any of the outputs while the printer is powered on. Double-check your wiring before turning on the printer again.
If you create a short-circuit at the EXTRA output, you will blow up the MOSFET that drives it. This happened in my case due to sloppy wiring while testing the PWM, and the transistor was shorted into a permanent ‘on’ state. Luckily I have experience in soldering SMD components, and I managed to replace the MOSFET, but this is not something you want to attempt if you have only soldered a few old-fashioned through-hole components.

description.text:
The OEM washers on the collar does nothing to prevent the collar from coming apart. My dogs are constantly loosing a contact and would come inside with the collar hanging on by one side. This replacement part helps prevent that!

This replacement part is split into two parts, for easy printing one! Also once installed with a few dabs of super glue, with the spikes on the bottom of the washer and the contact screwed into the recess, will help keep the contacts from unscrewing.

Installation
  1. Place bottom washer spikes down. It's a tight fit intentionally
  2. Twist the metal contact screw into the top washer, as far as you can. Aline the hex shape with the washer recess.
  3. Screw the metal contact/top washer into the collar. As you tighten it down the metal contact will slide into the recess.
  4. Along the seam of the two washers dab a small amount of super glue to bond it all together.

description.text:
This filament run off switch uses the Octoprint plugin filament sensor software (not the reloaded one). This is running on a raspberry Pi 3. I use a manual switch that I took the roller off of and bent the head forward to give the filament more room to glide over. It is some what of a sharp edge, but it seems to work just fine.

Filament sensor reloaded plugin, the one in the video:
All you have to do is cable up to the 18 and 20 pins, 24 GPIO and ground. The code uses the internal pull up sensor, so you should be good.

Old filament plugin, kinda unpredictable.:
I use a pull down resistor, with physical pins 1 3.3v, 6 ground, 32 gpio 12 in this config. See jpg for .octoprint/config.yaml file and wiring diagram. On octoprint command line enter gpio read 26 to check pin status, 1 will be filament there, 0 is filament gone.

I will be added some more housing options soon.

Video here: https://youtu.be/ChjwIGxnivw

Added a sensor 3 file, tweaked it a little to keep the filament a little straighter.

title: Da Vinci 1.0a Internal Raspberry Pi Mount

description.text:
Turn your Da Vinci 1.0a into a standalone, wireless 3D printer!

Mount a Raspberry Pi running Octopi inside a Da Vinci 1.0a printer to manage the printer through a web interface.

Updated: 1st October 2017 - Improved bracket "rpi_bracket_2.stl" with stronger PCB mount pads and relaxed tolerance on tray tab slots. (NB: photos still show older bracket)

Note that your Da Vinci MUST be upgraded to run Repetier firmware. Octoprint/Octopi CANNOT work with the stock firmware.

Requires:
1 x Da Vinci 1.0a or 1.0 (only tested on 1.0a) 3D printer running Repetier firmware.
1 x Raspberry Pi model B+, 2 or 3
1 x USB WiFi dongle (for Pi B+ or 2 only)
misc cables for power and USB.

Also requires:
Some knowledge of electricity and computer internals.
Acceptance that you will be voiding several warranties during this process.

Optional:
1 x Raspberry Pi camera
1 x >= 1 metre ribbon cable for camera

Thanks to @superwoodle for his Raspberry PI B+/2 mount!
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1205961

Printer:

Da Vinci 1.0a Repetier

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Note: Print the strengthened "rpi_bracket_2.stl", not the original.
Designed to be printed in ABS to tolerate the heat and vibration inside the electronics bay of the printer.

Post-Printing

Gently bend the dovetail supports after printing to break them free.

The joints should fit without excessive force however if they do not, clean out the female side of the dovetail a little with a hobby knife or emery board.

Post an "I made one" photo to help me feel useful.

Before installing the Raspberry Pi
  1. Install and TEST your choice of print server software. eg. Octopi
  2. Shutdown and disconnect the Pi.
  3. Mount the Pi on the tray with four small screws.
  4. Provide power for your Pi inside the printer.

You need to have 5V power supplied to your Raspberry Pi.
Option 1. (quick & easy) Use a regular Pi "wall wart" and run the cable into the printer case to the Pi.
Option 2. (slow & hard - but much neater) Use the plug off an old micro USB phone charger by cutting the cable to the required length, throw away the "wall wart" and solder the connector wires to the Da Vinci internal power supply. This can be technically challenging for some and has the potential to fry both your printer and your Raspberry Pi. Only try this if you have confidence in your soldering skills and your ability to find convenient +5V and ground terminals to attach to. Any smoke (and ashes) generated in the process is owned entirely by you.

Installation
  1. Remove the the rear electronics bay cover (two screws)
  2. Remove two of the main pcb mounting screws, top right and top centre.
  3. Put the bracket in place with the screw holes over the pcb mounting holes and replace the two pcb screws.
  4. Attach the Pi to the tray and decide on the best orientation for your needs. In my case, the Pi was mounted with the USB/Ethernet ports down to allow the camera cable to go up through the case,
  5. Install the tray with the Pi facing out (towards the rear of the printer) by sliding the tray dovetails into the bracket joints.
  6. Connect a USB cable from the Pi to the printer. (It is possible to squeeze it through some of the gaps in the case without any cutting.)
  7. (optional) Connect an Ethernet cable to the Pi.
  8. (optional) Connect the camera cable.
  9. Connect power to the Pi and printer.
  10. TEST!
  11. Take a photo and post a "make"!
  12. Re-attach the electronics bay cover.

Created in Tinkercad

https://tinkercad.com/things/jfEVR2tn3Lc

The idea of restricting access to my printer to only one computer (and only at home) seemed seriously stone age so I tracked down Octopi and Life Was Great. (I've been told that some printers require the insertion of physical USB sticks or SD cards but find that hard to believe in this, the Century of the Fruit Bat.)
Still had extra cables boxes and plugs cluttering up the desk so ..

Measured up the screw holes and available space inside the Da Vinci 1.0a, mocked up a bracket, removed the mounting holes from superwoodles' Pi mount to create the tray and created version 0.000000001 of the dovetail joints. This was followed by many "rinse and repeat" cycles to:-
a) get the tray dovetails to NOT break off along with the supports
b) produce joints that printed and fitted reliably (they may still be a little tight in places)

Hopefully all this work is of use to someone besides me!
Please take a photo and post a "make" if it is!

The Japanese, being infinitely more civilised, have solved this problem with sophisticated robo-toilets that provide soothing covering noise such as waterfalls, beach sounds and others.

Omni Directional Wheel 140mm Diameter.

I know there are other Omni wheels out there but I wanted as a wheel with more rollers so theoretically it would roll a little smoother. Fingers crossed. I also wanted one that would be bigger and easier to print. So I decided to design my own. I haven't tested with all four wheels yet (still printing), but the first one I printed rolls smoothly.

Note: This part requires your printer to be very well calibrated.

Hardware:
3mm filament for the axels
30 - M3 (8mm L) button head screws.
30 - M3 nuts.

Printed Parts:
2 - Bolted half
2 - Nut half
1 - spacer (optional - needed if rollers rub together)

Assemble:
Pretty Straight forward. First 2 steps are the most helpful.

1 - Rotate the two halves to see the best possible alignment (Wheel may not be perfectly round). Once happy with the alignment, mark the two halves with a sharpie for reference later. Make sure all inner and outer holes line up

2 - Make sure the all the nut and screws fit in the slots. Carefully clean up areas with a X-acto knife.

3 - Place all the wheels and axels on the first half on the of the wheel.

This is a good time to make sure all the wheel turn freely

4 - Using the alignment marks for step #1. Add the top half onto the assembled pieces.

5 - Carefully pick up the whole assembled part and add the screws and nuts.

6 - Repeat steps 1 - 5 for the next wheel assemble.

7 - Sandwich the spacer piece between the two assembles. I mirror the two assembles so the all the nuts are on the outside. The button head screws give better clearance for the small wheel.

8 - Enjoy :-)

Just starting out with painting of model kits and wanted to mimic the aligator+skewer+foam approach for spray painting.

This is my version of an aligator style clip to assist with model painting. Clip strength is firm and feels like a strong pinch on skin (nature's force meter!).

Model clip allows for different style of teeth caps to be added - Tall, Short and Wide.
Model clip can be attached to BBQ style skewer for easy stand-up

Short - Tighter grip in smaller spaces
Tall - Good grip, not so tight

Printed in PLA at both .2mm and 1.mm layer height. No supports required.
Raft only a consideration for the teeth caps, but not essential.

Bridging required for crossing section as there is a 0.4mm gap between middle and top/bottom ledges.Tried other clearances and found 0.4mm gave best clearance without need further cleanup.

Depending on your printer calibration minor clean up may be required. In my case ends of Pinch Clip needed slight shave to remove some ooze. Entry for teeth caps also need clean up.

NOTE : I'd imagine strength and elasticity would be better in ABS. The PLA works good enough but it can lose tightness on repeated pinching, although stretching back can mitigate.

Design using OnShape

Worked through a few design iterations. Main goal was to have a parameterised solution for the clip so I could adjust size and strength of clip. Happy with approach for pinch clip and annotation of part steps, the teeth caps not so regimented.

https://cad.onshape.com/documents/fafe24bbff1559c0c2c66a77/w/cd0bde23d50698f1a398028f/e/2cb721cb9f24073105b8263e

I found other sticks to be to short after printing. So I created this one, it is 70 mm high from the top of the Y-Axis and the bottom of the X-Axis bars. The X-Axis is only curves up on one side of the bar, while the Y-Axis curves down both sides of the Y-Axis half way.

I created the bar with no fancy curves, although it would save on material, that complicates the print and material is not that expensive. Keeping it simple helps with new printer owners who are trying to properly configure their printer.

description.text:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0atZU0YUqPw
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4ZkMkXbGZ0A
Okay -- this is a bad design. I'll update it or remake it and I thoroughly enjoyed making it. The goal of this was to design something 100% myself. I have no design training and that'll be obvious. I'd really encourage anyone to modify it as they see fit.

Now for the dirty dirty....

I printed all of the parts. I glued the auger and chute halves together. The splits made them easier to print. The auger housing gets glued to the bottom of the HOPPAH!!! Sorry, I'll serious up here....

The chute gets glued to the opening on the bottom of the auger housing. The stand is glued to the bottom of the auger housing on the flat part. The auger is inserted in to the auger housing and the cap glued over the opening. The servo / auger adapter is fitted to the servo. I then inserted the servo (a typical 9g continuous rotation one) in tot he servo housing and glued the housing to the back of the auger housing being sure the servo/auger adapter is fit in to the auger end. It'll make more sense when you try it.

Add candy, program an arduino micro 5v, and enjoy wondering why you went to the expense to make this when you can just open the bag and eat the candy.

OH!!!!!!!!! Very important note! I used SweetTart mini chewys as my candy but anything of that general size should work.

Be sure to ask of you have any questions -- I'll post pictures and a video of this in action in the next day or so.

I used a Prusa i3 MK2 printer. I hate supports so I positioned everything for non-support printing. I use 20% or 25% infill and I printed it in PLA. You can use ABS if you want. The servo auger adapter was 100% infill, 50% slower, random alignment, and the thinnest layer possible. I used regular old generic dollar store super glue.

I used Tinkercad to design this. I know it-s pretty lame. Make one better and share it with me!

Bookmark exercise to familiarize with Tinkercad editor for the McAllen Public Library 3D Printing course. As a Gundam fan, this only made sense. Zieg Zeon!

description.text:
Wanted to connect proper dust collection hose to my Shop Vac, but couldn't find an easy way to do it without destroying the Shop Vac hose that I had. Designed to use standard 2.5 inch dust collection hose with a hose clamp.

Upoaded STL files, as well as OBJ, STEP, and IGES files in case anybody wants to change the hose sizes.

UPDATE: I modified the hose end fitting to make it 2.4 inches, which makes it easier to get dust collector hose on as long as you use a pipe clamp

Printer Brand:

MakerBot Replicator 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2 mm

Infill:

50%

Notes:

Printed in PLA with 50% infill and 2 walls. Printed in three parts - the Screw End fitting, the Hose End fitting , and the Vac End fitting. Print as oriented in the .stl files.

Make sure that you calibrate your printer so that you can scale appropriately and the part dimenaions are accurate.

Assembly Instructions

The flat, non-stepped area of the Vac End fitting faces the Shop Vac and the flange bears against the male end of the Shop Vac port. The Screw End fitting is screwed on to the threads on the Shop Vac port, and then the Hose End Fitting is inserted into the stepped end of the Vac End Fitting and glued using epoxy or super glue.
